title: FSU's Dalvin Cook 'ready to go' for Louisville
text:
FSU's Dalvin Cook 'ready to go' for Louisville Safid Deen, Democrat staff writer 7:17 p.m. EDT October 15, 2015 FSU's Dalvin Cook runs a drill during Thursday's practice at the Dunlap Training Facility. (Photo: Joe Rondone/Democrat) 220 CONNECT 5 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
Florida State running back Dalvin Cook was a full participant in practice and will be “ready to go” for Saturday’s noon game against Louisville, Jimbo Fisher said on Thursday. 
Cook injured his hamstring two weeks ago against Wake Forest, and scored three touchdowns in his return against Miami last Saturday. He missed practice on Monday and Tuesday. 
Linebacker Terrance Smith (right ankle) and tight end Jeremy Kerr (concussion) were out of practice and will not play against Louisville. 
Smith will miss his second consecutive game. “He can’t play, but he’s getting close,” Fisher said of Smith. “He’s healing a lot quicker than I thought he would." Left guard Kareem Are (left knee), who missed the Miami game and has not practiced this week, is questionable. 
Chad Mavety continued to work at left guard with the starting offensive line. The other members of the line remained the same: left tackle Rod Johnson, center Ryan Hoefeld, right guard Wilson Bell and right tackle Derrick Kelly. 
•Freshman quarterback Deondre Francois was utilized on the scout team to replicate mobile Louisville freshman quarterback Lamar Jackson. 
“You got to tackle. You got to keep edges. It’s every play. You got to know if he’s got the ball or not, and he takes you off the guys who do have ball. He’s a heck of a player.” 
•Fisher said the Seminoles have had their best week of practice so far this season. 
“Practice has been good. Hopefully, knock on wood, we can take it to the field because we’ve practiced very well. Not perfect, but a lot better and a lot more mental toughness, a lot more execution and the things we’re doing.” 
The Seminoles (5-0, 2-0 Atlantic Coast Conference) and Cardinals (2-3, 1-1) will kickoff at noon, and the game will be televised on ESPN. Florida State coach Jimbo Fisher speaks with media after practice on Thursday, October 15, 2015.
